INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '9c00e4d9-cf5d-4e40-b8d9-173e989aa900',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Polygon NFT Standards — ERC-721, ERC-1155, and Metadata Optimization$escape$,
  $escape$Polygon supports two popular NFT standards: ERC-721 for singular, unique assets, and ERC-1155 for bundles and single assets. When creating an NFT, you must specify the standard in your contract. For example, using the Polygon SDK's ERC-721 implementation:
```typescript
import { ERC721 } from '@polygon-nft/sdk-core';
const nft = new ERC721('MyNFT', '0x...');
```
Metadata for NFTs is stored off-chain, but can be linked to on-chain using a URI. Polygon's `erc721Metadata` method simplifies this process.
```typescript
import { ERC721 } from '@polygon-nft/sdk-core';
const nft = new ERC721('MyNFT', '0x...');
nft.erc721Metadata('https://example.com/metadata.json');
```
Off-chain metadata storage is more flexible, but requires manual management and synchronization.$escape$,
